text: today is transgender day of remembrance. today we honor and remember the lives of those savagely lost due to transphobia. according to the human rights campaign, there have been 22 reported violent homicides against transgender individuals in 2018. in 1999, gwendolyn smith founded transgender day of remembrance to honor the murder of rita hester, a transgender woman in massachusetts. as scholar and advocate for transgender individuals, sarah lamble states, ‚Äúour task is to move from sympathy to responsibility, from complicity to reflexivity, from witnessing to action. it is not enough to simply honor the memory of the dead‚Äîwe must transform the practices of the living.‚Äù violence does not discriminate and neither do we in who we provide support to. access supports all survivors and victims of violence. please take a moment of silence honoring lives lost with us today. #tdor

text:
on today's podcast episode of the @pleasurerisingpodcast i chat with lisa foster from parillume‚Ñ¢ about sexual violation. .
in particular we discuss reclaiming who you are, healing and thriving after sexual violation.
.
we chat about her story of sexual violation, and i even open the doors for the first time on my own personal story with sexual violation. it is scary to sometimes share things which are so personal, but i am hoping this episode will open up the conversation even further - even if it's just a conversation we have with ourselves. .
lastly, we explore power plays at work, as well as what happens when you know the person who sexually violated you. 
and as always we close we three pleasure questions - what's your fav sex toy, what are you reading and what are you listening to right now. .
c'mon over to itunes and type in pleasure rising podcast to tune in to the show.

text:
as you prepare for your long car rides over the holiday weekend, add these 6 podcasts that will change how you think about your leadership journey to your podcast queue.
.
podcasts are a way of life for me‚Äîthey are both a pathway to dive deeper into the insights, ideas, and connections of my favorite topics, and an escape from my constantly-curious mind, a ticket to another world.
.
i‚Äôve listened to quite a few, and this is my roundup of the most practical and impactful episodes on leadership.
.
1. women at work. start with: make yourself heard. three female editors talk with guest experts about strategies that go beyond "speak up more," ways to assertively communicate your ideas in a meeting, and practical examples of how to confront someone who chronically interrupts you.
.
2. hidden brain. start with: ‚Äúwhy now?‚Äù. this episode explores the #metoo movement through the lens of the social sciences and will change how you think about being a woman in the office in 2018.
.
3. ask a manager. a call-in work advice show with practical, applicable ideas and language that you can apply in your everyday work. start with: i‚Äôm bad at taking feedback.
.
4. how i built this with guy raz. start with: drybar with alli webb. for when you‚Äôre curious about how to scale a business idea, listen to these stories behind some of the world's best-known companies.
.
5. dear hbr. start with: bad bosses. a research-based advice show for when you‚Äôre deciding whether to report a bad boss, flee, or find a way to stay and work together.
.
6. startup. start with: running a family and a business. for when you‚Äôre juggling career ambition with being there for your family. .
bonus: modern love. start with: one bouquet of fleeting beauty. because sometimes you need a break from thinking about work and leadership, and modern love is just the salve for your soul.
.
check out the roundup and episode descriptions on the women in leadership nexus blog - via link in bio.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
mgtow 101: how the dark side man thinks

i want to make it known that when i speak about dark side lovers, i'm usually speaking about the dark side sexuality perspective.

dark side doesn't have to be associated with bad things. view it  as her subconscious, her mind is water, her subconscious is deep sea and the deeper under the water you go the darker it is.

it isn't just about the sex, remember it's about being the man that she can be most vulnerable with. it's about being the man that can heal her, help her grow and evolve in many areas. since many men are not able to get a woman to that place many women will never come across men they can drop their mask around.

listen to this clip and peep the part about the woman having built up things in her life that she needs to get off. he is the type of dude women feel comfortable opening up and being vulnerable with.

this doesn't mean he is her dark side lover sexually, but he is definitely speaking as a dark side lover from the non sexual aspect. a man can be the non sexual dark side guy to a woman, without her even having sex with him. so the non sexual and sexual dark side man are separate from each other.

a woman can drop her mask and tell you all her vulnerable stories about her life, without divulging she likes to be pissed on and put on a leash.

it is always a give and take though. she gains by finally being able to release cuz she is with a man she can drop her mask with completely. imagine having to wear makeup and a costume every time you stepped out of your house. wouldn't it be a release to be able to just walk out without the extra stuff. women even feel this way about makeup, you use so much makeup for years and years it gets to point where you skin has been destroyed now you must wear the mask just to look pretty.

many men and women will never be able to be a dark side to their partner and that is why you have high value and you are the prize.

you should feel bad for the woman when she rejects you or doesn't recognize your value, cuz she will forever be on the conveyor belt of mediocrity, heading down a path of confusion without ever evolving, lacking a proper man to lead and teach her.

text: i love reading at airports and on airplanes, don‚Äôt you? on a recent trip to houston with some of my favorite girlfriends, i ordered @mskelseymiller‚Äôs book ‚Äúi‚Äôll be there for you‚Äù just so i could read it in-flight. i grew up a ‚Äúfriends‚Äù fan (swipe right to see that one time i got to sit on the central perk couch on the wb lot with my friend @staceygrosh), so naturally, i loved this book. it triggered so much nostalgia, but it was also just really, really well researched. (i learned so much about the actors‚Äô lives pre-friends, but also about the series‚Äô beginning, its newfound netflix-era popularity, its problematic depiction of gay characters (and lack of racial diversity), its post-9/11 impact, and how #metoo revelations eventually reached its writer‚Äôs room.) even for casual ‚Äúfriends‚Äù fans, you won‚Äôt walk away disappointed. what an extraordinary impact this show continues to have on pop culture (and on so many of us). tell me, what‚Äôs your favorite ‚Äúfriends‚Äù episode? (mine gets talked about in the book: the one with the embryos ‚Ä¶.see also, the one where rachel and monica lose the apartment). #gailsreads #gailsreads2018 #kelseymiller #illbethereforyou #friends #couldtherebeabettershow #howyoudoin #shesyourlobster

„Éª„Éª„Éª
‚Ä™join me on monday to protest #rapeculture by tying your underwear to your bag!

in reaction to the recent court case where a young girls choice of underwear was cited as implication for consent - we want to raise some noise on monday 26th november in solidarity with anyone affected by this thinking.

what we wear is not consent!

how to join in:

1. on monday 26th november we are asking people around the world to tie their underwear to their - handbags/rucksacks/totes to raise awareness to the cause. 
take a picture and share it using the hastag #thisisnotconsent and #thongsout.

2. join us on 26th november between 10-12 in a central london location (tbc) either in your underwear or wearing it over your clothes.

3. tell everyone you know to join in!
